      <hedline>
        <hl1>California's Power Lag</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Lynne H Church, president of Electric Power Supply Assn, disputes August 3 article on causes of California's power shortages (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''California on Edge of Failing to Meet Electricity Needs'' (front page, Aug. 3) sets forth the primary reason for the emergency facing San Diego this summer: a shortage of generating capacity.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''California on Edge of Failing to Meet Electricity Needs'' (front page, Aug. 3) sets forth the primary reason for the emergency facing San Diego this summer: a shortage of generating capacity.</p>
        <p>Although California was in the vanguard of power industry changes, its customers are temporarily caught in the worst of all worlds because the transition to full competition is taking too long. Power supplies are lagging because of lingering regulatory uncertainty and a lack of expedited permitting procedures.</p>
        <p>To speed the real benefits of competition nationwide, Congress must quickly adopt a set of comprehensive restructuring principles endorsed by consumer groups, the elderly, major corporations and utilities. Consumers in San Diego are now bearing the brunt of Capitol Hill's delay.</p>
        <p>LYNNE H. CHURCH  Pres., Electric Power Supply Assn.  Washington, Aug. 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
